{"type":"message","id":"04451aa6","parentId":"d8cdb44d","timestamp":"2026-04-10T01:36:21.822Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The folder structure is now `2026-04-10/` as the backup. Let me verify it's correct and also check if we should fix the git rm --cached issue with the embedded vibseref submodule. Also, the tag failed but the push succeeded - the main thing is the folder is there.\n\nLet me tell the user about the new structure and the one issue: vibesurf's embedded git repo (node_modules inside it) caused a git warning. For future backups this won't be a problem since the cached entry will be there. But we should probably address it.\n\nActually, the bigger concern is that the vibesurf skill has a `.git` dir inside its `references/` directory (because it was cloned as a git repo). \n\nThe script uses `--exclude='.git'` during rsync, so the .git directories should be filtered out. The \"embedded git repository\" warning was likely from a previous `git add -A` on the cloned repo, not from the rsync itself - since rsync excludes `.git`, those directories shouldn't have been transferred in the first place.\n\nActually, I think I see what happened. When I manually cloned the backup repo to `/tmp/openclaw-backup-git`, that clone itself contains `.git/objects/pack/` files, and those got synced into the `2026-04-10/skills/vibesurf` directory. The script is doing a `git add -A` on the backup repo which picked up the embedded git repo. I need to check whether `rsync` with `--exclude='.git'` actually prevented the `.git` directories from being copied in the first place.\n\nLooking at the files that got created - most are regular files in the vibesurf skills directory, but there's that `160000` mode file which signals a git submodule, plus the `git rm` warning about adding another git repository inside the current one. This suggests the `.git` directory from the source `skills/vibesurf/references/` folder did get copied somehow, even though rsync should have excluded it. I'm realizing the issue - the backup script was run multiple times, and after the first run added vibesurf as a submodule, subsequent runs tried to add it again as a regular directory, causing the conflict. The submodule entry (mode 160000) is still there in the commit, which means git treat the `.git` inside vibesurf as an embedded repo rather than a submodule reference.\n\nThe real problem is that the backup repo itself contains a `.git` directory, and when `git add -A` runs, it's picking up nested git repositories from the skills folder. I need to fix this by either removing the cached git entry or preventing these nested repos from being added in the first place."},{"type":"text","text":"新结构已生效。但有个问题需要修复——skills 里嵌入了 git 仓库。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wh0rn4vn7z8d_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/openclaw-backup-git && git rm --cached -r \"2026-04-10/skills/vibesurf\" 2>/dev/null; git rm --cached \"2026-04-10/skills/vibesurf/references/.git\" 2>/dev/null; echo \"done\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775784957806,"responseId":"062786fec39d00a90d54a3ef378928c2"}}
